The paper deals with information theory, coding theory, and graph theory, which are all relevant to computer science. The use of R{\'e}nyi divergence and the classical-quantum setting suggests that the paper may belong to the sub-category of cs.IT (Information Theory). The mention of sphere-packing bound and graph capacity suggests that the paper may also belong to the sub-categories of cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The use of Lov\'asz's bound and the mention of combinatorial results suggest that the paper may belong to the sub-categories of cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.QI (Quantum Physics).
